spath and possibly a processor path derived from `System.getProperty(\\\"java.class.path\\\")`. \\n\\nI have concerns about running tests under a native image, as `ToolProvider.getSystemJavaCompiler()` could be null. I'll need a solution that works for both JVM and native image environments.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring annotation processor instantiation**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to instantiate the annotation processor class reflectively, specifically `lombok.launch.AnnotationProcessorHider$AnnotationProcessor`. I can create a dynamic proxy for `ProcessingEnvironment` to handle a possible fake environment for the `init` method.\\n\\nHowever, since the outer class is package-private, I need to ensure I handle access correctly. The proxy must implement the interface properly, returning defaults to avoid null pointer exceptions. The challenge lies in ensuring this proxy returns an appropriate class name and handles any necessary method calls without causing issues with `delayedWarnings`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering proxy implementation**\\n\\nI need to make a proxy that implements `getMessager`, which can return another proxy for `Messager`. That seems feasible enough. I know that the initialization of the wrapper will call `instance.init` and then `super.init`, but it doesn't call `process`, which simplifies things a bit. Ensuring these proxies work correctly is crucial for avoiding any issues during the annotation processing, especially within the dynamic environment I'm creating.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating naming options**\\n\\nI’m considering using `MainTest`; even if it’s not unique, it might work since it's dedicated to `lombok.launch.Main`. However, there’s a possibility that there isn't a `MainTest` in the package. It feels a bit uncertain, but I think it could be fine. I really want to make sure the naming is appropriate and makes sense within the context of the code.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test file management**\\n\\nI think I should probably remove the LombokTest.java placeholder since it’s not doing anything. It makes sense to replace it with meaningful tests, especially since the user requested tests for dynamic access reports. I could use bash to delete the file, but I wonder if it might be better just to overwrite it with actual tests. I should also ensure that there aren’t any compile issues due to duplicate classes. Crafting the tests with minimal imports and comments will be key!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Drafting the ShadowClassLoader test**\\n\\nI’m working on the `ShadowClassLoaderTest.java`, which belongs to the `org_projectlombok.lombok` package. The first method, `loadsResourcesAndClassesThroughShadowLoader`, tests if the shadow class loader correctly loads resources and classes. \\n\\nI have specific assertions to ensure it finds the `java/lang/String.class`, checks resource availability, and validates class loading. For the second method, `fallsBackToAlreadyDefinedClassWhenDefiningDuplicateClass`, I’ll need to obtain the shadow loader. I’m curious if I need additional assertions regarding the self-skip behavior with resources!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring JUnit ShadowClassLoader**\\n\\nI'm considering how JUnit does not guarantee order, and I'm thinking about creating isolated `ShadowClassLoader` instances reflectively instead of using a singleton approach since the constructor is package-private. \\n\\nI can use reflection to create a separate loader each time, which might help with resource access. I’ll implement a `createShadowLoader()` helper function for this. From there, I plan to invoke methods on the `shadowClass` using reflection to manage class entries properly. It feels like a self-contained solution!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_N65ZWXCOxK4puRrm1Fsei85T|fc_0e0cded080c840030169f00634744c819f856e334885b789ad", "name": "bash", "arg